## Record Locking

The following entities use cooperative pessimistic locking to prevent concurrent edits:

<%_  entities.filter(e => e.pessimisticLock).forEach(entity => { _%>
- **<%= entity.name %>**
<%_  }); _%>

**How it works:**

- When you open a record for editing, a lock is automatically acquired
- The lock is renewed every **2 minutes** via a background heartbeat
- If another user already holds the lock, the record opens in **read-only mode** with a banner showing who holds the lock and when it expires
- The lock is released automatically when you save, cancel, delete, or navigate away
- If you close the browser tab without saving, the lock expires after **15 minutes**

Active locks are visible at `/admin/records-locks`. Administrators can force-release any lock.
<%_  } _%>

## Audit Logging

All create, update, delete, and restore operations on entities are automatically logged.

Access the audit interface at `/admin/audits`:

- **Audit Logs** tab — browse, filter, and compare changes; view complete history for any record
- **Statistics** tab — activity timeline, events breakdown, most modified models, top active users

Each audit record stores the old and new values, the user who made the change, IP address, user agent, and timestamp (UTC).

## Database Seeding

The seeding administration interface at `/admin/seeder` allows you to:

- Run any seeder individually
- Upload a CSV file directly from the browser
- Run multiple seeders in bulk
- Execute the full database seeder

> Running a seeder does not truncate the table first. To reseed from scratch, contact your administrator.

## Database Migrations

The migration administration interface at `/admin/migrations` allows you to manage database migrations:

| Operation | Description |
|---|---|
| **Migrate** | Run all pending migrations |
| **Rollback** | Roll back the last batch of migrations |
| **Fresh** | Drop all tables and re-run all migrations (**all data will be lost**) |
| **Status** | Show the current migration status |

> `migrate:fresh` is a destructive operation. All data will be permanently deleted.
